Holds - This is for NFTs i'm currently holding

When I get overwhelmed with notifs I will often mass clear them in the same order I explained them in these tweets until I feel like I'm back under control. The servers move fluently through this discord server pipeline otherwise

WL-Submitted - Once i've submitted my address for colletion, the server is placed in this folder. I check this folder most frequently when notifs pop up. These projects are close to launch and I want to be update to date on their community, timeline, and updates

WL - These are projects I've got a WL spot for. I check these notifications once every day or two to make sure i dont miss address submissions or a major announcement that changes my opinion on the project

Early/OG - This is a folder of servers that I found early and are building/growing. I keep close tabs on these because I may be in a position to grab a WL spot. If a notification goes off, I usually check it and make sure its nothing time sensitive then circle back later

Prospective mints is a collection of servers that I wasn't in early enough to secure the OG spot but I still want to mint. Whenever this folder gets notifications I check them when I have time in my day if its an announcement or update

We are all in a metric ton of discord servers. I have notifications on for all of them so I can stay up to date on whats happening but its impossible to read everything so I compartmentalize it with 5 folders:

Prospective mints, Early/OG, WL, WL-Submitted, and Holds

bUt HoW dO tHeY kNoW?

So, here is where my development background comes in and the tldr is youre fucked if they’ve executed well

We constantly track device IDs across log in sessions. Each ID is unique to a device. When an account is tied to two ID’s it’s flagged as cheating

Okay so, now that we’ve identified your new part time job let’s look at the fine print

In the rules and terms we all agreed to you, the owner of the ape _must_ be the person competing in the tournament otherwise your prize is forfeit so if you’re sharing with a friend, rip

Then you have 7 days to compete at 240 min a day, thats 1680 minutes total or 28 hours of gameplay if you are perfectly optimized. 

Whoever is closest to 28 hours of gameplay should be the 1st place winners on each side UNLESS the game gets much harder as we move forward

I did the math last night, you get 50 charges every 2 hours, which let’s you clear 10 levels (1 lvl per 5 charges) at a 2min~ clear time. So every 2 hours you have to play 20min to be optimally COMPETITIVE

You get 12 full recharges a day, equating to 240 min/day of play time

Tournament:

Okay so here’s where I’ve got a lot to say. The tournament for prizing feels underwhelming

It doesn’t actually feel like a tournament for who is the best player but a tournament for who has the most free time, and that’s not a fun competition in my opinion

Unless the game gets significantly harder after stage 100 (that’s all ive climbed as of now) then I’m not sure there is much skill involved here. Once you recognize the optimal strategy then it’s mostly a quick rampage through 10 levels per a stage and then on to the next one

Gameplay: 

Pleasantly surprised. I expected less depth so having 9 characters per team with N levels to play through has been refreshing. The various abilities are fun and different, but there is no balance in the game and clear from the start which apes are best

Choose wisely

The concept of a virtual joystick is good and the standard for these games. But the dash mechanic is unfortunate. I’m certain that whoever approved the dash mechanic being on the same joystick as movement is a literal ape

My knee jerk response on the first level was “wtf?”

Execution: 

Overall well done. As mentioned above the game is entertaining and has more depth than I expected in their game. I initially thought it would be a 1 level bullet hell survival game where you competed for time. So I’m impressed here. 

The controls need a lot of work

As a developer first and gamer second I’ve got dozens of thoughts about the execution here and most of them are good! 

I think overall this game shows what a successful team can do with their initial raise. It’s entertaining, has good depth, and appears to be mostly bug free

Waiting out a pending txn is also viable. Due to EIP-1159 you _should_ get a free cancel by waiting unless the contract is bad. 

Typically a contract will revert any txns that are pending after a sell out happens. These reverts act similar to cancels and you pay very little

A cancel WILL protect your eth by sending a simple txn at a higher gwei which will negate your previous mint txn that was sent at a lower gwei. 

I have sent mint txns that cost $1000+ that I then canceled for $75~. It's a safe bet if you're concerned and want to protect your eth

Canceling a txn at its core means to send a txn to YOURSELF for 0 eth using the same nonce as your mint txn

THESE ARE CHEAPER TXNS THAN MINTS. A mint txn executes complicated code on chain, cancel txns dont so they're cheaper

2k gwei mint txn will cost more than 4k gwei cancel

If you speed up your txn you are replacing your existing txn with another FASTER txn. Your goal here is to out gas the other txns and confirm sooner to secure your mints, be prepared to pay a premium and up your gas from the recommended

I always manually input my gwei/priority

If supply is running out, gas is increasing, and your txn hasn't confirmed you have three options:

Speed up, cancel, or wait

Let's look at each in order, starting with speed up

Priority is crucial to getting your txns processed faster and confirming during a gas war, but you wont be refunded any priority like you will gwei so be sure to understand what you're doing

Once your txn is sent you need to monitor two things: Existing supply and gas prices

When you send a higher priority value you are WILLINGLY giving that money to the miners to pick up your txn faster and fit them in to an earlier block

That earlier block may be confirmed at 190~ gwei so it wont use all of your gas, but it WILL consume all of your priority tip

A txn has two values now: gwei, priority

Gwei is the gas price to fit in to the block

Priority is how much of a "tip" you give to the miner to process your txn faster
